The '''Research Laboratory for Archaeology and the History of Art''' ('''RLAHA''') is a [[laboratory]] at the [[University of Oxford]], [[England]] which develops and applies scientific methods to the study of the past. It was established in 1955 and its first director was [[Edward Thomas Hall|Teddy Hall]].<ref name="RLAHA webpage">[http://www.arch.ox.ac.uk/rlaha.html RLAHA page on the Oxford University School of Archaeology website]</ref> The first deputy director was Dr Stuart Young, who was followed by Martin Aitken in 1957.<ref name="RLAHA webpage" />
The Laboratory is currently directed by Professor [[Christopher Bronk Ramsey]]. Among the areas of research it has been involved in are:
* [[Radiocarbon dating]] * [[Luminescence dating]] * [[Characterization (materials science)|Materials analysis]] * [[Palaeodiet]] * [[Archaeological geophysics]] * [[Uranium-series dating]] * [[Diagenesis]]
The laboratory includes the Oxford Radiocarbon Accelerator Unit (ORAU), which carries out [[radiocarbon dating]] using an [[Accelerator mass spectrometry|accelerator mass spectrometer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Oxford Radiocarbon Accelerator Unit |url=http://c14.arch.ox.ac.uk/embed.php?File=|publisher=Research Laboratory for Archaeology and the History of Art}}</ref> The Laboratory publishes the journal ''[[Archaeometry (journal)|Archaeometry]]''.
